author: alterfritz72

title: Minecraft Night Light - Single Extruder Multi-Color Print
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is an experimental project that has the potential to damage your machine if not done correctly, please proceed with caution when printing this design

The main body of this lamp is printed over 5 stages in 3 colours without being removed from the bed. The only parts removed during those 5 stages are the outer square and any brim generated by your slicing program.

This part was designed to be used with Slic3r, however any slicing program that can center an object based on it's outer dimensions can most likely be used. It makes use of the retraction Z lift function to avoid colliding with other sections of the print. This is not an ideal situation but it does make the print possible without gaps.

The STL models themselves are OK however Slic3r doesn't like joining the cubes, so small gaps are present. Slic3r frequently fails to render the most basic meshes even remotely correctly, this is a minor example of that case.

You can use anything to light up inside of it, I use a small section of 12v natural strip light on an AC adapter.

Stages 1 and 5 are printed with black filament. Stages 2 and 3 are printed with red. Stage 4 can be natural or white.

Stages 1 - 2 - 3 - 4

100% Infill
2 mil Z Lift

0 mil Minimum Travel After Retraction

print_settings.Notes:: This model is at risk for falling over when you encounter stringing. Adjust temperature and retraction settings for a good result.

description.text:
The parameterized mouthpiece by CKirby - now improved.

Note that this errors in customizer without a clear message. It does not in openSCAD. Still trying to find out why.

What I changed:

  • four outer design shapes: straight, straight with rim for text edge, rounded and concave
  • A resolution can be chosen for the sampling from the bezier curves forming the cup, rim and outer shape
  • much higher default resolution. Takes 10 minutes to render on my i7 macbook
  • default settings correspond to a wide shallow commercial sounding bass trombone piece, a bit like the Marcinkiewicz ETB-3 mouthpiece but a bit more shallow.
  • when printing one-piece, adds a raft along the top of the shank. That way, a slicer can add support below that, so your mouthpiece will not fall over during printing.

The original Bach-like oversized rounded outer design shape is no longer included, but is easy to add if you want.

See photso for a test print at 0.15mm layer thickness. I hope to do a much higher resolution print soon for a very smooth result.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

If you need to add the raft for added stability, set the slicer to enable support

This model is at risk for falling over when you encounter stringing. Adjust temperature and retraction settings for a good result.

title: Ikea Ivar Under Shelf Bracket for LED Light

description.text:
A basic shelf bracket for Ikea Ivar shelving that provides a mounting point for LED lighting strips to illuminate under the shelf. The bracket positions the light at a 60 degree angle. Print two of them and use small zip ties to secure the LED light strip through the hole in the brackets.

You can purchase the 21 LED light strips from Amazon. They're quite nice, small and very bright and even lighting.

Ikea Ivar shelves have gotten 1mm smaller over the years it seems. The file labeled "new" fits shelving I purchased a year ago. The file labeled "old" fits shelving purchased over 10 years ago.

Printer:

description.text:
This was inspired by LoboCNC's Frankenstein Light Switch Plate: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:649284

Designed to suit UK styles of light switches.

Printer:

Creaty CR-7

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

The supports were required for the handle, all other shapes are self-supporting.

The measuring up is based around a Slim Profile 1 Gang Light Switch from Home Base, whilst "own brand" package the switch has "Folio" branding on the inside. The overall size was limited by the print bed... this is the biggest thing I've printed.

The switch piece is aimed at giving the opportunity for "tuning" for differing switch panels and profiles - the bodies appear to be similar.

The original design had a lip all the way around for securing under the switch, the notch was removed to allow the plate to be passed through without un-wiring the switch.

The Front and Back plates reasonably snap together for me but I've allow for a captive M3 screw to allow the plates to be more securely fastened together. In this case with a wing nut for looks ;)

Remove the screws holding the switch to the wall (take care live parts may be exposed - isolate the circuit at the fuse box).

Slip the switch through the back plate and re-secure to the wall. If you're using the M3 screws to secure the front and back place - fit the screws before fitting the back plate!

Clip on the Front Plate (secure fasteners if used)

Put Handle and Switch Piece in place and fit pin.

Note: If you're using a differing switch as the basis of your construction you may want to check dimensions or amend the switch piece to suit any differing profile.

title: Memoclip "Clothespin" cnc/laser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A giant clothespin is a funny idea you can see from time to time. And it's really easy to build a double sized copy yourself. I used 2 mm aluminum wire for creating the spring, which results in a pretty unstable construction. So I inserted some neodyn magnets to enforce the clip.

The build was done on a desktop cnc-machine from Stepcraft from 6.5 mm baltic birch plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute.

Keep in mind that the "build stl" is meant for three dimensional viewing only.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

Für Liebhaber der älteren Eichermodelle.

This is the cage arm connector from a Mini-Plane paramotor. it connects the outside of the cage to the cage support arms on either side. there are 4 of these on a Mini-Plane.
So I tried power launching in no wind and the risers squeezed the cage into the prop. I had a spare prop but no plastic fitting so I sketched it up and printed it. works as a backup while replacement parts arrive from somewhere on the internets.
my trusty 3D printer had me back in the air the next day :)

• Smash one (or more) of the cage connectors on your Mini-Plane paramotor, preferably with a prop strike for maximum effect.
  • download the .stl
  • print on your 3d printer (I used PLA)
  • heat the part / end of the rod and insert into the piece to ensure a tight fit.
  • assemble and go flying :)

Feel free to print the mirror object if you need a double sided thing.
Once again, if you need help, please let me know!

If i push the Powerplug of my Ulti a Little bit to the left, he will turn off....
I saw an other Solution for this Problem here but with 2 Problems:
1:It was for a straight plug and my one is angeld
2: You are not able to use the USB Plug ! (I have the Original without +)

So my Solution is working fine for me ! As you can see on the Pictures ist small easy to print, Need just 1 screw and you can still acces the usb plug !
I also put a heavy Ring at the bottom of the Printer so it wount shake so hard.

You can srew trough the wall (see Picture)

The screw was 29mm Long and selfcutting

Needed another peace of bleed block for my Shimano SLX brakes (M675) so just printed it. Should fit all brakes using G01S and G03S pads. List bellow found online, tested on M615

BR-M987 - BR-M615 - BR-R515 - BR-M985 - BR-S700 - BR-R315 - BR-M785 - BR-CX75 - BR-M675 - BR-RS785 - BR-M666 - BR-R785 - BR-M8000 - BR-M9000

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 original kit

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

200 um

Infill:

50 % <

Notes:

In upright position the hold tab is small area and if printing only this model from ABS, there will be problem with layers not cooling fast enough. Better to add to plate with other models. When applied cooling fan slow still slightly warped.

Printing on side, need to support side tabs. Your pick.

Also possible to mod model (source uploaded) and get rid of tabs. Already successfully bleeded brakes using hex wrench as spacer tabs to keep spacer in center of caliper are not must have.
Used piece purchased with set of M615 brakes as reference and replicated measurements.

description.text:
UPDATE REV5: This was fitted especially for my X frame, but I think it could benefit other X frames with the antenna bottom mounted. This design includes a few improvements, which are made mostly for X frames:

  • Cable guide from the left top guides the cable away from potential prop damage, and acts as a bumper in case the antenna brushes against the prop.
  • Right side bumper increases antenna survivablity in case it is pushed in the right side prop which can hit the antenna from the top.
  • 2cm extended base moves the top bar of the "T" shape further away if it slides between the two props. This appears to me to be very common for X frames. Without it, it seems like certain death for the antenna when it's pulled backwards.
  • 13 deg forward tilted base helps to keep the antenna higher and safer from prop damage as it needs to be pulled harder to actually reach prop level. It also makes the antenna pads stick further away from the frame, and be less shadowed by the back arms, which should improve signal reception.

In addition to these, I did minor fixes to the model and stitched it better in place where it was slightly broken, which caused bumps and creases in the final printed part.

UPDATE REV4: Uploaded a revised version when I had to go back to this form factor from the v-shape, as low mounted v-shape on a compact X-quad build gets the antenna pads too close to the props. The revised version is sturdier, doesn't require to clip off any bits, slightly curvier and appealing, bridges better during unsupported prints and requires less hot glue to secure the pads to.

I broke the original on its first flying session, and then got the antenna cable chopped up by the props, so I picked up a caliper, measured everything, and created an alternative design, inspired by the original, but not exactly the same.

This design has a slightly lower, narrower profile than the original, and so far has withstood crashes much harder than what it took to break the original.
It has a cable channel that goes through the side of the top frame part, so the cable is safer from prop damage.

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

This was designed to be printed without supports, if your printer + filament of choice are good for bridging.

I used FormFutura's CarbonFil which is super stiff.

Speed: 40 mm/s

Nozzle: 0.4mm

Walls: 5 (Bridging works much better with a lot of walls)

Slicer: Cura

I used the "change at Z height" plugin to reduce the printing speed to 50% for the first 3 layers of top bridging (should be layers 97-100 at 0.2mm).

Rev4 was printed with FormFutura's TitanX, which should be very impact resistant, but less stiff than the carbonfil. I think its properties are a better fit for this application. Printed with a 0.6mm nozzle at 40-50mm/s, 50% infill

Installation

Update: for rev4, just clip off any loose bits that might prevent from the pad to slide easily into place, then, make sure the antenna pad can slide through the top side of each of the two "slits" that are made to hold the antenna side opposite to the wire connection, and use a sharp knife to make them big enough to slide through otherwise.
This version, unlike the previous and the original, requires you to slide in each antenna pad through the center section of each fixture. Apply a moderate amount of pressure on the pads to slide them from the center through the slit, and then back down to the base.
You should still use a dab of hot glue to secure the top pad's cable to the "channel" at the side of the top fixture.

After printing, clean well any loose bits and strings from the area where the antenna patches need to slide into, and then: (Use the provided images for reference)

(with a wire cutter)

  1. Clip off the part supporting the bit that slides into the rubber mount.
  2. Clip off the the two supporting pillars that go across each antenna patch fitting, but leave about 2mm at the base of them at both sides (for better securing the patches when they slide in).

(with a sharp knife)

  1. Trim and finish and bits that secure the patches in place, so they allow just enough room to slide the patches easily.

(Optional)

  1. After sliding the patches in, use a bit hot glue to secure the top antenna cable to the channel, so it doesn't get mauled by the props, and more to secure the top antenna patch in place.

comments.text: What's the recommended material for this? If this was already answered somewhere, I couldn't find it.
comments.author: jevring

comments.text: I used FormFutura CarbonFil which is a PETG+CF composite, but this could work with ABS, PC, Nylon or any other kind of a more durable and impact resistant filament.
comments.author: jevring

comments.text: I had a couple of these printed in ABS, and one in PLA. I tried to flex the ABS one and it snapped instantly. I don't know if was a bad material or bad print or what. I wanted something that wasn't too soft, as I assumed that the antennas would just fall out during a crash. Might have to re-evaluate that decision if the other prints fail in a similar way.
comments.author: nbiton

comments.text: If it snapped really easily then it's probably a bad print (check the settings), or you printed it in the wrong orientation. It should be lying flat like the model is originally set. That said, a good hard hit will snap one of these almost as easily as the original breaks. I've steered away from whale tail setups a while ago due to the durability issues.
comments.author: jevring

comments.text:
The shop that printed it for me printed it standing in the top of the T, so to speak. As you mention, that's probably a mistake.
Also, as for it being a brad print, I think you're right. The place where it snapped didn't look great.
Thanks anyway for a great design =)

magnets my friend.
heat m up,

description.text:
This is a modified version of the card holder from @PhantomEbay Which looked like a good starting point. Newbie box-checking problem fixed, so properly indicating 'remix' now. :)

I cleaned up a bunch of extra faces, and rounded off a bunch of edges. Also added a chamfered key-ring hole, and did a test print as shown. The lower layer under the reg SD cards was a bit thin, so added a bit to that too.

Also wanted to remove the sensitivity to slot-width for a friction fit, so added some tension-bumps to each bay to give a slight bit of extra friction. Should help for print-to-print variability.

Will tweak again if I come up with any other brainwaves, but feels pretty good now.

UPDATE

Use the xxxx_D.stl file if you have downloaded an earlier one. Found that the tension bumps were a bit too tense in the altered version after a second test print.
If you printed the earlier xxxx_C version, just sand the bumps down a little bit.

Notes:

Printed at .1mm, but prob the common .2mm will work fine too.

In spite of the overhangs, I didn't use supports due to the tight spaces. There are a few tendrils to clean up, but it appears to not have super negative impact on the final result. I used a raft in my print, but it shouldn't really matter if you have a nice smooth build plate with good adhesion.

Clean up with a knife

Because I recommend to print without supports, you'll need to clean up a few loose tendrils with a sharp knife after you've finished the print.

title: Filament-Role-Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Hi.
I want a Spoolholder where you can easily and quickly change material.
In addition I want no spools on the backside because I didn't have much space on the back and I ever have to move my UM2 when changing material.

So this spoolholder is for all Filamentroles which width is smaller than 80 millimeters.
The hole in the middle should be 52 millimeters or larger. (Brand who fit: REC; Verbatim; Ultimaker; Innofill; Colorfabb; and for sure other which I don't know yet.)

Also the holder has got a ring on the frontside to put filament through.
First: Filament can't jump off role.
Second: UM2 feeder needs filament from the underside.

Hint for combine:

  • put the spoolholder on the table,
  • turn rack that the Ring for Filament is on left side,
  • put the role with pole on the rack and put the filament through the ring - so that the filament unroll clockwise!

Part dimensions rack: Length: 200,5 mm; Width: 100 mm; Height: 126,5 mm

I want a solid part. So my settings were:

Top Solid and Bottom Layers: 7
Outline/Perimeter Shells: 3
Skirt: 2 Lines only at first Layer; 4mm away from part
Minimal Infill Length: 1mm
Printing Speed: 3300mm/min - 55mm/s
Nozzle diameter: 0,4mm
Material: PLA - Brand: REC
Temp Nozzle: 215°C
Temp Heatplate: 65°

If printing both parts at once:
Retraction Vertical Lift (in Z+): 1,00 mm (If possible)
(Pole: In the first / last Layers can it be that the outer Lines come up a little bit)

  • better printing one by one.

Printing time (both parts at once): 20h 25min
(With: Nozzle diameter: 0,4mm / Layer 0,2mm / Top+Bottom Layers: 3 / Shells: 2 /
Infill: 15% / 3500mm/min = 58mm/s -->you would need probably about 10h 50min)

And I think, printing with a Nozzle 0,8mm will be faster...!

It works very well and the spool moves very easily!
(Tested on meanwhile over 200 hours)

At least:
This is my first upload.
So I hope it works on your printer.

If you have any questions or something else - leave a message and I try to answer as soon as possible.

Happy printing!

New Version / Thing files

Now its a new version / thing file online (04.09.17)!

With settings like first version:
~13hours 32min
~28m Material

--> After that print I can say:
Aside from the fact that my print istn't perfect because of feeder doesn't really worked all the time (little plastic-dirt in gears) and nozzlediameter became bigger, it works.

Now I have changed the nozzle and cleaned up the feeder. I'll printing a better one soon to show you more pictures.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1OOb1g6mGHN

Plastic Bottle Base:
I would look in the kitchen or grocery store for a round plastic container where the cap fits the plastic bottle base.

Plastic Bottle:
I used a 1 quart plastic vinegar bottle for one and a plastic beverage bottle for the second. Remove plastic safety ring. Drill 2-1/4" holes through bottle side (and cap if necessary) about 5/8" from the end of the cap. Location of holes will will determining liquid height. Liquid closer to the bottom of the flower is best.

Wine Bottle Base:
Used a cork type wine bottle. Just push the open end into the base. The base will provide about 7/8" of liquid in the bottom container.

Flower:
I printed a flower @ 60% speed for about 12 minuets and then reduced to 40% speed for the stem. Slow speeds will give better results. A timer will help. Flower #1 has smaller petals and are for bottle clearance when necessary.

Tapered Mounting Rings:
They have a relief for getting closer to the lid edge. 2 per flower.

Plastic Bottom Container:
Need a shallow container about 1-5/8" deep. Tupperware or equal will provide the most durable container. Drill 1/2" flower holes in the lid far enough in from the edge to clear the bottom part of the container when put together. Center hole should be large enough to allow the bottle base to sit on the container bottom.

Hanger Brackets:
Knob sticking out of top bracket is for recessed container bottoms. Reverse for flat bottoms. Brackets were printed at 80% speed.

Hanger Twine:
Cut one piece of the appropriate length and a second one twice as long. Double the long one and knot all three strands to form a knot with loop. String the hanger brackets and knot or use Cord Lock.

Cord Locks were used on the wine bottle build. Be sure and secure the cord back around the lock for safety after all is adjusted. They can be found at this link.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1730077

Cleanup necessary. Print speeds will effect the final fit up. Used crazy glue where needed. Scale for you needs.

Liquid is 1 part sugar to 4 parts water. Most Hummingbirds have a tongue as long as it's bill.

Project inspired by: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:77439

Where are you from?
Please upload what you have made as I'm interested in what other people do with this.

title: Adafruit 7" Portable HDMI Monitor Case Remix for use as a larger camera monitor

description.text:
Remixed the case for the Adafruit 7" HDMI Touch Enabled Monitor -- makes use of a spare camera LiPo.
Adafruit has a 5" version they run off of a camera LiPo and a 7" version they run off their own battery pack. This case is a mix of the best of both of those project plus some fine grained control over backlight brightness.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Standard

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Printed with a brim to minimize warping.
Used translucent blue PLA since I wanted to show off the electronics and self built nature of this project.
I printed it with supports because the power switch holder is much higher than the other switches and I didn't want it to droop. Was easily removed and worked out great.
Removed brim and any supports

Using the battery holder dimensions from the STLs for the 5" screen I was able to modify a version of the 7" case back to have the same holes for the Canon LP-E6 battery holder and a hole for the wires to pass through. I also doubled the thickness of the case back as the original 7" back was too thin/flexible for my liking. The extra stiffness helps the battery holder stay securely fastened. I also deleted the screw stand-offs for the PowerBoost board that is not needed for this remix.
For the case top I added 2 more switch holders so each of the hacker points -- 50mA, 50mA and 25mA could be toggled separately. I also removed the large hole for the PowerBoost and added yet another switch holder so I could control the on/off power from the side where all the cabling is located.

description.text:
I loved the Socket Orgainzer by WoodmanXI, but my Craftsman socket set was quite a bit different than that one and I needed to customize to hold all of the sockets in my particular set.

I ended up having to build the 3d models again, since I'm not talented enough with SketchUp to alter the existing files. I based the layout, dimensions, etc on WoodmanXI's original design.

I'm still considering if I should model up trays for the various extensions, ratchets, and spark plug sockets.

Socket sizes:
Standard Short 500 12pt - 1/2 inch drive - 3/8" to 1" in 16th increments
Standard Short 375 12pt - 3/8 inch drive - 1/4" to 13/16" in 16th increments
Standard Short 375 8pt - 3/8 inch drive - 1/4" to 1/2" in 16th increments
Standard Short 375 6pt - 3/8 inch drive - 1/4" to 1" in 16th increments

Metric Long 500 12pt - 1/2 inch drive - 13mm to 19mm

description.text:
ok there are actually two designs here.

these are an easier alternative than the somewhat over engineered bearing types that can be found everywhere (unless your planning on spinning your filament spool at race car speeds you really dont need bearings ffs)

one suits the more conventional style filament spools while the other is for the smaller centre holed variety.

both designs are intended for use in a horizontal format and work exceptionally well.

additional hardware required for each design:-

5x m4x15mm bolts
1x m4x30mm bolt
2x m4 locking nut
1x Meccano 3" pulley (http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/Meccano-Vintage-Part-19b-Pulley-Black-/191196205568?hash=item2c842e9200:g:IPgAAOxy3cJTiGgf_

Printed in ABS but PLA will work just as well, the only benefits to ABS is that it sands quit well which means you can get rid of all those sharper edges cleanly which makes the spools more comfortable to use.

remixed_from.author: CEOjameson2501
remixed_from.title: Ultimaker 2 Filament Holder for Reels With Smaller Diameter Holes

title: Ultimaker 2 Reel Holder with reenforced bracket

description.text: Our Ultimaker 2 reel holder broke off. In searching for a replacement design, I found a lot of designs that have very thin support for the L-shaped part that is stressed by the weight of the reel. This design has a thicker reel support to reduce the chances of breaking.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

I printed upside-down (see photos) so that the parts that the reel slides over have the least friction. It did take a while to pull off all the infill, but the result was worth it. I printed in ABS for strength, but I expect it will work in PLA as well.

This is a new design, based on the general approach of several existing designs on Thingiverse.

I did two things to reduce the chance of breaking: I made the vertical bar of the top snap as thick as possible, and I made the holder a full circle so that the leverage of the 1kg reel is reduced (a lower fulcrum).

Incidentally I removed the non-functional side snaps (they're pushed, not pulled, by the reel), increased the space between the Ultimaker and the reel so the reel cleared our filament feeder, added a larger spur on the end to keep the reel from sliding off, and (just for our uses) reduced the holder's length to again reduce the leverage of a 1kg reel of filament (shorter Moment of force).

I haven't optimized the amount of filament required, and you will likely need to change the diameter or length of the holder for your filament. I'd welcome a design that used less filament, but kept the essential thick L-shaped part.

author: shano7

description.text: Deck out the top floor of your Makerbot Rocket with this three piece set - it has everything you need to guide your mission to the moon. For the steering console, chairs, and the rest of the series, check out my other things: http://www.thingiverse.com/PrettySmallThings

Control Tower:
The right and left towers are easily printed with 2 shells (total) and no infill. The arch is best printed on its back as oriented. The geometry is just at the printable limits of my machine without support. Use acetone or glue to adhere together. Desk:
Print Base & Top with 15-20% infill. The base just exceeds printable limits, but is easily cleaned up. My base print with zero extra shells printed better than the print with one extra shell. Cabinet:
Print all STLs. Test fit Wall into base & top. Check length of hinge "pins" on doors and trim if necessary. Adhere wall into Base. Drop hinge pins of doors into holes in base. Carefully adhere top to wall, capturing the pins. Elements are designed to be interchangeable. Create your own layout! Decorate with your favorite paint medium. My prints are in silver, black and natural ABS with some decorative help from black and silver paint pens + whiteout.

remixed_from.author: jbswaff
remixed_from.title: HOTEND MOUNT for Airwolf HD2x... Convert to E3D v6 + Volcano

title: HOTEND MOUNT for Airwolf HD2x... Convert to E3D v6 NO Volcano - THIS IS FOR THE NON VOLCANO VERSION
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a modification to Josh's original which may be found here with complete instructions on assembly.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:956219

The short and sweet of it:
if you want to take your Airwolf HD2x and print out something greater than 315C - then you need a different head assembly. If you want to go FAST get the E3DS V6 Volcano and use Josh's great STL files found on the link above, along with complete instructions.

These files in this post are if you want to print in Hi Fidelity and at High Temperature, and also if you want to print with carbon containing material, Then get the E3DS V6 from the good folks at Filastruder :
http://www.filastruder.com/products/all-metal-e3d-v6-hotend

Be Sure that you read all of the instructions on Josh's post and note that my Bill of Materials is similar to his, but with the addition of one additional M3x45 socket head and M3 Hex nut. I wanted to put a leveling post on my version of this, like the original.. We may not need it, but why not put it in there?

YOU WILL NEED:
(2x) M3x20 Socket Head Cap Screw
(3x) M3x45 Socket Head Cap Screw
(5x) M3 Hex Nut
(4x) Small zip ties
(2x) E3D v6 + Hotness

Like Josh said, proceed with caution as you will need to modify your software on this deal!
http://wiki.e3d-online.com/wiki/E3D-v6_on_Airwolf_HDx_/_HD2x

http://www.soliforum.com/topic/12034/upgrading-your-airwolf-hdx-hd2x-hotend-to-e3d-v6-volcano/

On8/20/16: If there are problems with your hot ends wiggling a bit with the original design and you don't want to shim it, i have uploaded a modified front piece which has taken the flats down by 0.5mm. Fixed the problem.

Printer Brand:

Airwolf 3D

Printer:

AW3D HD

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

80%

Notes:

I printed with PC-ABS with GREAT results. If you haven't printed with PC-ABS, then trust me, all your current frustrations will be gone once you make the leap from PLA and ABS.

80% infill may be overkill, but we are going for maximum strength here. I also did:
.5mm nozzle
1.5mm walls and top and bottom
speed of 65

Nozzle Temp: 300C
Bed Temp: 140C

For the support, find a setting that will support the insert hollow on the "back" part but does NOT support the inside of the holes that the zip ties go through. On Cura, that was 85 degrees for my printer, Grid at 20%, EVERYWHERE... If I went to 75 degrees it will fill the holes that the zip tie goes through...

USE AIRWOLF's WOLFBITE MEGA for PC or PC/ABS. THIS STUFF IS AWESOME and prevents all the other issues with 3d printing. Magic stuff.

comments.text: Thanks, this worked with Airwolf AW3D HD. This is a bit different shape than the original, so had to add small extra blocks to carriage blocks to get limit switches to work.

description.text:
I was having some clearance issues with the Wiha Stand and one of the longer hex drivers, so I decided to create some feet to add an additional 5mm to height. This also allows the stand to be slid across your bench without worrying about scratching the surface.

This can be reused for the edge of any other 14-gauge sheet metal.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

15%

This is a seal I made for a contact lens container.  If you use the type of contact solution that is peroxide based, you need a special container to put it in.  The container has a relief hole on the top.  When I travel, the solution always leaked out of that hole.  Now with this seal I created you can confidentially toss your contact lens container in your bag without worrying about it leaking and ruining your contacts.

I printed this in PLA with 30% infill and .2mm layer height.  No supports needed.  For the seal itself, just get a rubber bumper for a cabinet door or drawer from the hardware store, shouldn't be more than a few dollars.  Place the bumper in the depression of the object once you print it, and snap it on to your contact lens container case.  See the attached Sketchup model to check any dimensions you need.

print_settings.Notes:: Print time for the bottom was about 4 hours and 1.5 hours for the top.

title: Pi 3 Case for 5 Inch Touch screen

description.text:
I looked around for a Pi 3 case that would support a 5" screen but was unable to find one (lots of 3.5" and 7" screen models). So, I decided to make my own.

I used the original design from "Raspberry Pi Display Case" for my basis. I recreated it from scratch with the exception of the original cutouts for the power/HDMI/audio ports and the cutout for the ethernet/usb ports. Everything else was created from scratch using Sketchup.

I did not create an access door for the microSD card, so I designed the top to fit snugly but it does not "lock" onto the bottom case.

Here is the screen I purchased/used:
https://www.amazon.com/Kuman-Resistive-800x480-Display-Raspberry/dp/B01F3EKJIA/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1470006672&sr=8-1&keywords=kuman+5%22+touch+screen

UPDATE: I just uploaded v2 (top and bottom are in the same file). This version has a lip on the top and bottom which allows the two pieces to fit together better than the original version.

I have also added top and bottom v3 (with a place for the MicroSD extension, so that the MicroSD card can be accessed from outside the case (near the USB ports. I purchased an MicroSD extension from Amazon (see below). The only drawback to using this extension is it comes with a real long ribbon cable. There should be room on the same side of the case as the extension mount to place the cable and keep it out of the way. I carefully removed the black plastic housing that came with the cable and created a slot that it will fit in snugly.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01D9J8KQE/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Printer:

Hictop Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I used Cura to slice it and left supports everywhere turned on. The only support it added was for the lower HDMI and power cutouts.

Print time for the bottom was about 4 hours and 1.5 hours for the top.

author: Jscherry

title: Shane's Coral Frag Plugs
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This Thing is a coral frag plug that is used when propagating (i.e. "fragging") coral in the saltwater aquarium hobby.  
Coral fragments are either cut or broken off of the mother colony and then glued to this frag plug using cyanoacrylate gel (superglue). The resulting fragged coral plug is mounted into 14mm eggcrate that is submerged in the saltwater aquarium where it is left until it is either traded with another hobbyist or sold at a frag swap.
I have uploaded four variations on a concept that I have been toying with for what might be useful to a coral farmer.  I am keenly interested in optimizing this concept so that it Works for those needing a good, quality, multi-purpose coral frag plug so please leave comments on how I might improve this Thing.

Additional fragging tools that might be of interest:
  • Joanne's Frag Plugs by engineglue: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16959
  • Hemostat by CaptainKirk: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13152
  • Tweezers - either the ones by SimonH http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7768 or http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:638 by hoeken
  • Pliers: russrobot http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11332, Starno http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1091, or tonyv http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12266
  • A detachable version this frag plug: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:17313
    • If you see other tools of interest, please let me know in the comments and I'll add links to them here. This particular thing is a mashup of the Pin Connectors V2 by tbuser (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10541) and the Knurled Surface Finishing Library by aubenc (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9095). When I saw the Pin Connectors, I knew I wanted to model a coral frag plug using it at some point as it should be (relatively) easy to make something that would fit and snap lightly into a 14mm eggcrate hole. The Knurled Surface Finishing Library gives the top of the frag plug a nice surface finish for easy gripping in a wet environment. I have currently uploaded four concepts (along with printing plates for each):
  • One hole and one slit in the base
  • One hole and a cross-slit in the base
  • Four holes centered on the cross-slits in the base
  • Four holes 45 degrees off of the cross-slits in the base
    • The current features of these frag plugs are:
  • Knurled edges on all frag plugs for easy gripping when wet
  • At least one hole in each top for either:
    Â Â Â Â a) attaching a tyvek or ziptie tag for identification
    Â Â Â Â b) using a rubber band to hold down the coral frag
  • A large central depression for holding glue
  • Axial depressions for added attachment points for the coral as it attaches
  • A "pin" base that lightly "snaps" into 14 mm eggcrate using a 14.5 mm lip. This lip is there to keep the frag plug in place in case its placed in a high flow area.
  • At least one slit in the base in case one prefers to slide the plug onto the eggcrate instead of into the eggcrate hole.
  • Some plugs have cross-slits so that they can also be placed on the cross-piece of eggcrate.
    • Print with 100% infill using either ABS or PLA. Please, if you use this, leave feedback on how I can improve the design! :)

author: Fire300z

description.text:
A remix of Emmett Lalish's venerable heart gears, this adds spots to the center block and the inside of the gears to aid in assembly.

When assembling the gear heart it can be difficult to tell some of the pieces apart or determine where they go; the two smallest gears in particular are nearly identical and are easily confused. To address this, each gear has from one to four small dots surrounding the pin hole; big and small gears that are opposite each other have the same number of spots.

The revised SCAD file is included, as well as STLs for all three gear ratios in the original: 1:2, 2:3 and 5:6.

For the hand cranked version, I believe that you do not use the center block or bottom piece, as these are unique to the cranked version, but the other pieces should work just fine.

description.text:
This attachment allows the spool to spin freely on the Monoprice Maker Select Mini (Malyan M200). Reducing stress on the spool side should give you one less thing to worry about when printing.

This attachment fits all but one of my spools, and is easily removable when a small spool needs to be used.

Additional Supplies:

  • Two skateboard bearings $4.99USD for 8 on Amazon (likely cheaper to just get 2 from a skate shop)
  • Approx 10cm section of 8mm dowel (9/32")
    • Update: folks report a 5/16" dowel to work well. If a little loose, a strip of tape around the circumference tightens things up. Thanks Jared Allen and Zachary Walton!
      *Update 2: another user reports that a BIC pen is a perfect fit

  • 1.2mm wall thickness

  • Rotate models to lay flat

Pop the bearings into position and mount them on the rail. Feed the dowel through the center hole and see how everything fits together.

A touch of adhesive will help hold the bearings in place.
Lots of testing!

comments.text: cura isn't able to slice this, I rotated this so it lays flat then printed with and without rafts and wasn't able to print it. Looks like there's a little ridge on the back side that's preventing it from printing properly.
comments.author: pengc99

comments.text: As a follow up, I increased the initial layer width to 0.3mm and was able to print it correctly. Default in Cura is 0 which prints the first layer the same size as the normal layer height (0.1mm), changing the initial layer to 0.3mm made sure the raft was generated properly.
comments.author: pengc99

comments.text: I've noticed that Cura glitches like that sometimes. I'll try and slice a model and a raft or supports won't show up in the preview correctly, and I found that resetting the initial layer height fixes it. You can then set the layer height back to the setting you had, or at least closer if it still glitches.

description.text:
Another update 08-08-2016. Someone of Ultimaker hinted me on this model: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/um2-dual-fan-shroud . The airflow of this design has been proven bij computer simulation. The original UM2+ fanshroud design is made to be folded with steel sheeting. The model on this youmagine link is heaps better for 3D printing.

Update 03-08-2016: Use the _fatter.stl file, the original model is made for steel sheeting, which is so thin that it doesn't work for 3D printing. The _fatter file is made fatter, which makes the whole thing a whole lot stronger! :)

All rights of this model go to Ultimaker. I did not model this!

This is a direct conversion from their STEP file on their Github page, completely unmodified.

Use a brim and full support structure, and a as sturdy as possible material. The one i printed in PLA is a bit flimsy, but looking good!

description.text:
THIS IS AN OLDER VERSION - the newer version is here, though be warned that it is untested:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1723705

I like Excelvan filament. I don't like how big their spool's hub opening is. My spools would drag on the table when using my printer's included spool holder.

So... This adapter neatly snaps into the Excelvan's hole (print two - one for each side) and reduces the diameter of the hole significantly.

The adapter should be reusable if you carefully remove it. I've done so without delaminating and mine are printed in PLA.

The print is simple and shouldn't take super long. I actually print without my cooling fans in hopes that inter-layer adhesion is improved. The result is still extremely clean looking.

Hope this helps someone out there!

title: Sandhill Crane Sculpture
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This sculpture is made from a short film I'm creating. The film does not involve 3D printing, but the model was made and posed and looked nice, so I wanted to have a physical piece of it.

I tried several times to print this without breaking it into pieces, but the very thin legs and small detail, especially on the back foot, always tricked the printer into failing. I offer this sculpture both as a single model which may cause you trouble when printing, and as 4 separate pieces that must be glued or welded together, and will ultimately look best with surface finishing of some kind.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

The base and lower body will work without rafts, but the head needs supports, and the back leg is too narrow to stand on its own on the print bed.

I welded parts using a soldering iron and extra extruded bits of PLA filament. It helps to have some sticky putty to hold pieces together in place as you make initial welds.

Solvent or glue would also work, but curing time would mean you'd need something to hold the parts together as it cures.

The joined pieces will leave a visible border as you can see from my photograph. I recommend sanding, then applying a surface treatment like Smooth-On XTC-3D. Once that cures, sand again, prime, and paint!
The model is based on collected photographs and videos of Sandhill Cranes. Modeling was done in Maya and Mudbox. Character was rigged and animated in Maya, and this pose was selected for printing.

comments.text: Thank you thank you!  My mother loves Sandhill Cranes and lives near a flock of them, and I was really hoping to find a model of one to print for her.  I'll be damned if they aren't the weirdest birds I've ever seen.  Can't wait to print this and give it to her.

I have created three different models, two which are pictured above:
-Blast doors
-Sewage Grate

Also the game board was made from a sheet of Blue Insulation foam cut into 2' x 2' squares that was painted with elmers glue, dusted with sand, painted black, then dry brushed.
Print at any resolution though beware of peeling, stick down to a game board and then sand/flock around/over some of the details.

title: Steam Turbine Model - Low Pressure Rotor V2
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a beautifully detailed Low Pressure Steam Turbine Rotor. The STL files are in 1:18 scale and includes as much detail found on a real machine as possible.

This model is designed to be assembled with glue. All parts except LP_bore_plug, 20T_blade, and 20G_blade should be glued together. Superglue + clamping for 10 minutes worked well for me.

LP_bore_plug is designed to be removable with a slight friction fit.

20T and G blades are secured in place with a T-slot groove. The assembly was designed to fit 58 blades but I was only able to insert 55. Don't glue these in place because you may need to replace broken blades at some point in the future.

See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1676760 for the rotor stand.
See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1666208 for the lifting beam.

This is V2 of the low pressure steam turbine rotor. Parts are generally comparable with Version 1. V1 is here- http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1616343

Pros compared to V1:
Greatly reduced part count
Reduced printing time
Reduced assembly time
Reduced sanding time
Reduced plastic volume
Interfaces between sections are better hidden

Cons compared to V1:
Some realism is lost. The radii between stages have been changed to 45° chamfers. The chamfers have been kept unrealistically small in order to be printable without supports. For most people, this is not noticeable.

Update 2017/04/23 Corrected scaling of 19T. Fixed 16G/16T to be mirror blade orientations.

author: jlsilicon

description.text: "What do we say to our terrific presenter, class?" "Thank you!" These words have been spoken hundreds of times by every teacher around the world. While having a classroom of polite children show appreciation is in fact quite rewarding, receiving a customized, 3D printed thank you note is even better!
I find Tinkercad to be best for my design needs, but you will no doubt select the tool which works best for you. If needed, you may borrow my design here.
NGSS

This lesson introduces students to the basics of 3D design while also sharing the amazingness that is 3D printing with community members who visit your classroom or school. Objectives Students will design (or contribute to the design) and print a thank you thing for a classroom visitor. Audiences Elementary (teacher guided design)
Middle and high school (independent design) Subjects Design Skills Learned (Standards) NGSS: 3-5-ETS1-1 (Third through fifth grade)

• Following a presentation by a classroom visitor, brainstorm some of the key take-away lessons learned. These ideas can be incorporated into the design.
  • Have students sketch ideas for a thank you thing fitting to the purpose or interest of the presenter (card, medal, trophy, etc.). If working with younger children not yet capable of designing independently, merge several ideas. For older students allow them to each design their own thing, or work in teams. For instance, in the included example Ms. Clark, a wildlife biologist, gave a presentation on local owl species. To thank her for her time, our thing featured small owls and eggs.
  • Introduce Tinkercad and allow time for students to complete the tutorials. Extension: Increase the design challenge for older students by requiring that things use no more than a set amount of material. This will require students to run the slicer program multiple times, further improving skills.
    Optional Have students start with a template, such as the four part jigsaw thing above. This will decrease the time spent designing from the ground up, also also creating a more collaborative thank you thing. Another option is to import a thing, such as this trophy from Thingiverse user tc_fea, and add suitable text or decoration.
  • Print, and if needed redesign and reprint, thing(s). If possible, have the guest speaker return to the class to receive their thank you thing(s) for added impact, allowing students to present to the presenter how a 3D printer works or a bit about the design process.
    • A medal my kindergarten class helped design for our school secretary in honor of Administrative Professionals Day.
Elementary: 2-3 sessions Middle and High School: 5-10 sessions
No prior design skill is needed.

Looking for more information on teaching design in middle and high school? Check out this piece by designer Jamin Hegeman. Rubric & Assessment Since this lesson is primarily about introducing students to design and 3D printing, I encourage assessment be limited to participation and teamwork, and avoid grading on design or finished product. However, a reflective writing component could follow the lesson to check to understanding. Handouts & Assets For those working in elementary and looking to set the stage a little, here are 19 picture books on gratitude. The Tinkercad file for the four part jigsaw can be found here.

print_settings.Notes:: you should print this print with as low infill as possible that still ensures dimensional accuracy, as air is a great insulator. These are mass produced somewhere in China, so I can't verify that your fridge will fit; it should, and the design should also be useful for anyone wanting to design their own peltier cooler with a 60mm fan and 70mm heatsink combo. If you have a tendency to overextrude you might have to sand down the joint between the top half and the two bottom halves, as it has absolutely 0 play.

description.text:
Do you have one of these? Do you find it's insulation properties to be lackluster? Did you ever wish it were harder to open, and looked more like a giant obelisk? Do you like unnecessary amounts of work for a small amount of gain? Do you often pose rhetorical questions to yourself in thingiverse descriptions? Well boy do I have the project for you!

I snagged one of these little USB fridges for a project before I realized that it's literally just a straight 200ma of DC to a peltier module and a small fan with a heatsink. It ended up being underpowered for my needs, but I wondered how much cooling you could actually coax from it. Enter, the monolith. This print is designed to be operable by one hand and provide the maximum amount of insulation in a reasonable print. The two halves of the peliter module are relatively well isolated and the beverage can itself gets 20mm of insulation on every side - not too shabby. It also now accepts full 12oz red bulls!

If you're looking for even more cooling you could easily swap out the peltier module for a more powerful version - ebay and even amazon have some cheap ones. search for tec1-1270*, where * is the amperage you want. you may have to upgrade the fan if you do so, I haven't done this myself yet. If you want some more immediate satisfaction and have a 12V 2A power supply laying around, the stock module is a tec1-12702, so you should be able to just solder that bad boy in place of the usb power instead

Notes:

you should print this print with as low infill as possible that still ensures dimensional accuracy, as air is a great insulator. These are mass produced somewhere in China, so I can't verify that your fridge will fit; it should, and the design should also be useful for anyone wanting to design their own peltier cooler with a 60mm fan and 70mm heatsink combo. If you have a tendency to overextrude you might have to sand down the joint between the top half and the two bottom halves, as it has absolutely 0 play.

I made this design with something I'd call positive-space modeling for lack of a better word. Instead of designing an enclosure around the parts, which often leads to unparametric, throwaway code, I designed a tolerant 3d model of the parts I wanted to enclose and applied the difference between my design and the parts to achieve the desired effect. This ends up being a lot easier to customize and troubleshoot, and I definitely recommend it.

title: Pi 2 Case - slim with customization options

description.text:
My first pi case was a purchased, laser-cut box that pops together. Within a week, it had broken at the joints. After having problems with other cases that I downloaded and printed, I decided to make my own.

As marked in the description, this is still a Work-In-Progress. My end-goal is to finalize a case that can be opened/closed repeatedly without wear-and-tear. For now, this is done with M3 screws and requires drilling on the Pi (ulp!) with a 1/8 bit. I like the M3 cap screws, but that's just a "style thing" and I will probably offer a version that does not need drilling.

Options at this time include a plain cover, vented pi logo cover, and solid cover with a partially inset pi logo. Future update will include cam, gpio access, reset switch options.

Note: current design is slimmer than the case shown in photo (top of cover has been lowered to align slightly below top edge of ethernet port)

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Simple Black

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 or .3 layer height

Infill:

20% infill recommended

Notes:

pi logo should be printed at 97% to allow fit on the non-cutout lid with inset.

on the cutout lid version, I printed the logo at 97% with a brim (recommend at least 8 lines) so it can be fastened with epoxy from the inside.

One other touch: The Pi logo was printed in red t-glase. On my Printrbot simple, I printed this piece with temp of 242, no fan, 20% infill, speed 25 to get a translucent effect.

Fitting the Pi to your case

This design is still being fine-tuned to give a good fit on the ports but not too tight. You may need to do some minor filing to so it will sit in properly. If the board does not go in easily or seems to stand up on the GPIO side, check the fit on the HDMI port. It may need to be filed at the top edge a little for this to set in place properly. Once the board is in place, check the SD card slot alignment. This design has a "trap" surrounding the sd tray, but the alignment should be close enough that the card can be inserted/removed without a lot of trial-and-error.

It does not show in the photos, but the bottom of the case has hex nut countersink recesses. After cleaning excess flashing out of these holes, I was able to shim in the M3 hex nuts by pushing them in using the face of a small craft hammer.

As mentioned before, the case in photos was assembled with M3 screws (18mm) which required drilling of the Pi PC board holes with a 1/8" bit. You should be able to use different hardware if you don't want to drill your board.

DesignSpark Mechanical Parts Database

DesignSpark mechanical had a 3d parts database feature that allows you to incorporate parts into your design. The power of this feature is that you can pull dimensional references from the part specs, and also view the part inside the design. One of my goals for this project was to learn how to design a case with proper port-cutouts that are reasonably aligned.

My first step was to decide how deep to make the stand-offs for the circuit board. I used the Dimension function in DesignSpark to see how deep the Ethernet port anchors sink below the bottom surface of the board, and allowed for a little extra room. After checking the board length and width with Dimension, I made a basic box and practiced tracing port cutouts by projecting the edges of audio, hdmi, and power ports to the side panel of the case.

Although having the Pi 3d model to draw from was a huge help, there were still adjustments to be made to allow for real-world discrepancies. The power port is inverted on the drawing. Even after reversing the port cut-out in my design, I had some challenges getting it properly sized and centered. I made a copy of the side panel and did some test-prints to help test changes and re-traced the pattern from the test panel back to the case design.

The original box was oversized, had peg-style standoffs and oversized ports (see top-left item in figure). Modified the original design to include separator walls for the usb/ethernet ports.

The logo was taken from the 3d part model and enlarged to fit on the cover. The 'solid' version of this logo is only 1 mm thick on the recesses, to allow for light to shine through. I am working on adding an LED that will illuminate the logo when the power is on.

Case designed from scratch using 3d Pi model as reference.

I know there are a lot of slim cases already out there and this may look a bit generic. I hope that the ability to vent or even do a back-lit logo brings a little originality.

I'm working on improvements still and constructive criticism, and suggestions for options/revisions are welcome. This is a great learning experience!

last disclaimer: any cover should be printed with top side facing the bed, stand-offs pointing up. This will be corrected in the solid cover version stl file.

print_settings.Notes:: Nothing special required.  Miles and miles of filament passing thru could eventually grind down the channel, so I guess tougher is better.  I used HIPS.

description.text: Here is a simple filament runout sensor. I was going to use an optical sensor, but I print using clear filament sometimes, and wasn't sure how it would work. In any case I had several of these microswitches laying around and decided to use them. These have a flag, but no roller (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00UBWSMKC/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1). Note that I slightly bent down the end of the flag, so that the filament would slide either way, but you want the primary direction to be so that it goes with the flag. I put a mark on the outside of the assembly so I would know which way to the filament goes. To secure the two haves, you need 3x M2x12mm bolts and nuts. I created versions for 3mm and 1.75mm filament. It will clamp onto entry or exit tubing. I assumed 6mm tubing for 3mm filament and 4mm tubing for 1.75mm filament.
